</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Aortic stenosis is the most prevalent valvular cardiovascular disease affecting the population over the age of 65 years. Transcatheter aortic valve replacement (TAVR) was developed as a minimally invasive surgical intervention to treat aortic stenosis in patients at high risk for surgical complications. Although the most commonly used approach for placement of a transcatheter aortic valve is in retrograde fashion via a transfemoral approach, narrowed luminal diameters, extensive atherosclerotic disease, or significant tortuosity may limit use of this route. In these patients, alternative methods including subclavian, transaortic, and transapical approaches should be considered. An understanding of these access routes and their respective indications and contraindications allows the radiologist to provide additional preprocedure measurements and images to help guide placement of the valve.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180059">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180059">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1a.jpeg" height="1234" width="1768" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1b.jpeg" height="1234" width="1770" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1c.jpeg" height="1245" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1d.jpeg" height="1388" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1e.jpeg" height="1339" width="1612" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1f.jpeg" height="1339" width="1435" aria-labelledby="fig1f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1f</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1g.jpeg" height="1470" width="1708" aria-labelledby="fig1g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1g</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1h" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig1h.jpeg" height="1470" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig1h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1h</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR in a 74-year-old woman. Transfemoral access was contraindicated, and multidetector CT was performed in preparation for subclavian delivery of the aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the subclavian artery (arrow) in the deltopectoral groove. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows measurement of the aortoventricular angle through the aortic valve relative to a horizontal line through the left ventricle at the same level. A measurement of 44° is suitable for a left subclavian approach. <b>(d–g)</b> Coronal <b>(d, f, g)</b> and axial <b>(e)</b> images show measurements along the course of the subclavian artery from just distal to the deltopectoral groove <b>(d)</b> to the origin of the vessel from the aorta <b>(g)</b>. Note the relatively minimal degree of calcification involving the subclavian artery. <b>(h)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the aorta and subclavian vessels shows a minimally tortuous vessel, making this left subclavian artery suitable for valve placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig1h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig2.jpeg" height="1175" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 2</span>. Narrowed subclavian artery in an 82-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows a narrowed subclavian artery (arrow), which measures less than 6 mm secondary to a dense atherosclerotic calcification. This finding prevented TAVR from being performed via a left subclavian approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig3a.jpeg" height="1397" width="1788" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 3a</span>. Kinked subclavian artery in an 83-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Coronal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show an excessively kinked left subclavian artery (arrow). The degree of kinking and tortuosity prevented performance of TAVR from a left subclavian approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig3b.jpeg" height="1397" width="1162" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 3b</span>. Kinked subclavian artery in an 83-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Coronal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show an excessively kinked left subclavian artery (arrow). The degree of kinking and tortuosity prevented performance of TAVR from a left subclavian approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig4.jpeg" height="1199" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Valve angle greater than 70° in an 83-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Coronal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows a valve angle greater than 70°. This valve angle is not suitable for performance of TAVR via the subclavian approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig5.jpeg" height="1258" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Subclavian artery dissection in a 48-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows bilateral dissection of the subclavian arteries (arrows). This is considered a contraindication for performance of TAVR via a subclavian route.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig6a.jpeg" height="1501" width="1813" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Subclavian artery occlusion in a 60-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Coronal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show chronic occlusion of the subclavian arteries (arrows in <b>a</b>, <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), which prohibits delivery of the aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig6b.jpeg" height="1501" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Subclavian artery occlusion in a 60-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for subclavian TAVR. Coronal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show chronic occlusion of the subclavian arteries (arrows in <b>a</b>, <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), which prohibits delivery of the aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig7.jpeg" height="1514" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 84-year-old man. Reformatted 3D image with soft-tissue rendering from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material shows the preferred location for aortotomy (arrow). Dashed line = ascending aorta proximal to the innominate artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig8a.jpeg" height="1498" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 80-year-old man. Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material, obtained from the skin surface <b>(a)</b> to the aorta <b>(f)</b> in a peel-away fashion, help localize the aortotomy site (arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) relative to the chest wall while also highlighting anatomic structures that may be encountered along the way.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig8b.jpeg" height="1498" width="1191" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 80-year-old man. Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material, obtained from the skin surface <b>(a)</b> to the aorta <b>(f)</b> in a peel-away fashion, help localize the aortotomy site (arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) relative to the chest wall while also highlighting anatomic structures that may be encountered along the way.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig8c.jpeg" height="1498" width="1288" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 80-year-old man. Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material, obtained from the skin surface <b>(a)</b> to the aorta <b>(f)</b> in a peel-away fashion, help localize the aortotomy site (arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) relative to the chest wall while also highlighting anatomic structures that may be encountered along the way.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig8d.jpeg" height="1486" width="1260" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 80-year-old man. Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material, obtained from the skin surface <b>(a)</b> to the aorta <b>(f)</b> in a peel-away fashion, help localize the aortotomy site (arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) relative to the chest wall while also highlighting anatomic structures that may be encountered along the way.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig8e.jpeg" height="1486" width="1259" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 80-year-old man. Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material, obtained from the skin surface <b>(a)</b> to the aorta <b>(f)</b> in a peel-away fashion, help localize the aortotomy site (arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) relative to the chest wall while also highlighting anatomic structures that may be encountered along the way.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig8f.jpeg" height="1486" width="1181" aria-labelledby="fig8f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8f</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR in an 80-year-old man. Three-dimensional reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material, obtained from the skin surface <b>(a)</b> to the aorta <b>(f)</b> in a peel-away fashion, help localize the aortotomy site (arrow in <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>) relative to the chest wall while also highlighting anatomic structures that may be encountered along the way.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig8f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig9a.jpeg" height="1440" width="1789" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Midline location of the aorta in an 84-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the aorta located directly posterior to the midsternal line (dashed line). The location of the aorta in the midline makes this patient a candidate for a mini-sternotomy. <b>(b)</b> Reformatted 3D image with soft-tissue rendering from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material shows the anticipated location of the mini J sternotomy (black arrow, dashed line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig9b.jpeg" height="1440" width="1357" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Midline location of the aorta in an 84-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the aorta located directly posterior to the midsternal line (dashed line). The location of the aorta in the midline makes this patient a candidate for a mini-sternotomy. <b>(b)</b> Reformatted 3D image with soft-tissue rendering from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material shows the anticipated location of the mini J sternotomy (black arrow, dashed line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig10a.jpeg" height="1360" width="1691" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Aorta located to the right of the midline in an 82-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the aorta located to the right of the midsternal line (black dashed line). Given that greater than 50% of the aorta is located to the right of the midline, a right anterior thoracotomy (white dashed line) is the preferred access for placement of a transaortic valve. <b>(b)</b> Reformatted 3D image with soft-tissue rendering from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material shows the anticipated location of the right anterior thoracotomy (dashed line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig10b.jpeg" height="1360" width="1462" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Aorta located to the right of the midline in an 82-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the aorta located to the right of the midsternal line (black dashed line). Given that greater than 50% of the aorta is located to the right of the midline, a right anterior thoracotomy (white dashed line) is the preferred access for placement of a transaortic valve. <b>(b)</b> Reformatted 3D image with soft-tissue rendering from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material shows the anticipated location of the right anterior thoracotomy (dashed line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig11a.jpeg" height="1365" width="1725" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Extensive calcifications in a 74-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Sagittal multidetector CT image <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show extensive atherosclerotic calcifications of the ascending aorta (arrows), which prevent delivery of an aortic valve via a transaortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig11b.jpeg" height="1365" width="930" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Extensive calcifications in a 74-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Sagittal multidetector CT image <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show extensive atherosclerotic calcifications of the ascending aorta (arrows), which prevent delivery of an aortic valve via a transaortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig12a.jpeg" height="1354" width="1079" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Extensive calcifications in an 80-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> 3D reconstructions of the aorta, derived from multidetector CT with contrast material, show a suitable site for access (arrow) despite the extensive calcifications. The patient successfully underwent transaortic TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig12b.jpeg" height="1354" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Extensive calcifications in an 80-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> 3D reconstructions of the aorta, derived from multidetector CT with contrast material, show a suitable site for access (arrow) despite the extensive calcifications. The patient successfully underwent transaortic TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig13.jpeg" height="1298" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Pleural plaques in a 76-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows pleural plaques (<b>*</b>) secondary to prior asbestos exposure. Pleural plaques limit access via a right anterior thoracotomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig14a.jpeg" height="1300" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Coronary artery bypass graft in a 62-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Sagittal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and sagittal 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show the course of the coronary artery bypass graft (<b>*</b>) and distances from the existing sternal wires (arrows). Given the close proximity to the sternal wires, a sternotomy approach was avoided and the patient underwent a right anterior thoracotomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig14b.jpeg" height="1738" width="1501" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Coronary artery bypass graft in a 62-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Sagittal multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and sagittal 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show the course of the coronary artery bypass graft (<b>*</b>) and distances from the existing sternal wires (arrows). Given the close proximity to the sternal wires, a sternotomy approach was avoided and the patient underwent a right anterior thoracotomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig15.jpeg" height="1665" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Right internal mammary artery bypass graft in a 73-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Three-dimensional reconstruction shows a right internal mammary artery bypass graft (arrow) located directly posterior to the sternum and anterior to the aorta. The presence of the bypass graft prevented placement of an aortic valve from a transaortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig16a.jpeg" height="1185" width="1654" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 16a</span>. Aortic dissection in a 67-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> multidetector CT images with intravenous contrast material show a preexisting aortic dissection (<b>*</b>), which prevented placement of an aortic valve via a transaortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig16b.jpeg" height="1185" width="1495" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 16b</span>. Aortic dissection in a 67-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> multidetector CT images with intravenous contrast material show a preexisting aortic dissection (<b>*</b>), which prevented placement of an aortic valve via a transaortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig17a.jpeg" height="1350" width="1642" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 17a</span>. Aortic aneurysm in an 82-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal oblique <b>(b)</b> multidetector CT images with intravenous contrast material show an aneurysm (<b>*</b>) at a prior aortotomy site, which prevented delivery of an aortic valve via a direct aortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig17b.jpeg" height="1348" width="1508" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 17b</span>. Aortic aneurysm in an 82-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal oblique <b>(b)</b> multidetector CT images with intravenous contrast material show an aneurysm (<b>*</b>) at a prior aortotomy site, which prevented delivery of an aortic valve via a direct aortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig18a.jpeg" height="1082" width="1827" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Aorta located in the left hemithorax in a 68-year-old man who underwent evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show an unusual location of the aorta (arrow) in the left hemithorax. This location was a result of prior surgery and radiation treatment for lung cancer. This altered anatomy is not suitable for valve replacement via a direct aortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig18b.jpeg" height="1082" width="1525" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Aorta located in the left hemithorax in a 68-year-old man who underwent evaluation for transaortic TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material <b>(a)</b> and 3D reconstruction <b>(b)</b> show an unusual location of the aorta (arrow) in the left hemithorax. This location was a result of prior surgery and radiation treatment for lung cancer. This altered anatomy is not suitable for valve replacement via a direct aortic approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig19a.jpeg" height="1084" width="1211" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the location of the left ventricular apex (arrow) relative to the chest wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Corresponding images show the distance from the left ventricular apical myocardium to the chest wall <b>(b)</b> and aortic valve <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig19b.jpeg" height="1084" width="1245" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the location of the left ventricular apex (arrow) relative to the chest wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Corresponding images show the distance from the left ventricular apical myocardium to the chest wall <b>(b)</b> and aortic valve <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig19c.jpeg" height="1084" width="1254" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows the location of the left ventricular apex (arrow) relative to the chest wall. <b>(b, c)</b> Corresponding images show the distance from the left ventricular apical myocardium to the chest wall <b>(b)</b> and aortic valve <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig20a.jpeg" height="1345" width="1437" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR in a 71-year-old woman. Coronal oblique 3D reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the ventricular apex relative to the chest wall (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the potential thoracotomy site (white line in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig20b.jpeg" height="1345" width="1514" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR in a 71-year-old woman. Coronal oblique 3D reconstructions from multidetector CT with intravenous contrast material show the location of the ventricular apex relative to the chest wall (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the potential thoracotomy site (white line in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig21a.jpeg" height="1352" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Pericardial calcification in a 57-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows extensive pericardial calcification (<b>*</b>), which limits access to the left ventricular apex. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the left ventricle highlights the extensive pericardial calcifications (<b>*</b>). The patient was deemed not suitable for transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig21b.jpeg" height="1352" width="1448" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Pericardial calcification in a 57-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. <b>(a)</b> Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows extensive pericardial calcification (<b>*</b>), which limits access to the left ventricular apex. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional reconstruction of the left ventricle highlights the extensive pericardial calcifications (<b>*</b>). The patient was deemed not suitable for transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig22a.jpeg" height="1370" width="1514" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Thrombus and thinning of the left ventricular apex in a 63-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> multidetector CT images with intravenous contrast material show a thrombus in the left ventricular apex (arrow) with thinning of the apex, likely from prior myocardial infarction. These findings prevented performance of transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig22b.jpeg" height="1370" width="1836" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Thrombus and thinning of the left ventricular apex in a 63-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> multidetector CT images with intravenous contrast material show a thrombus in the left ventricular apex (arrow) with thinning of the apex, likely from prior myocardial infarction. These findings prevented performance of transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig23a.jpeg" height="1334" width="1532" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. <b>(a)</b> True aneurysm in a 66-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image shows a left ventricular true aneurysm (<b>*</b>), a contraindication for transapical TAVR. <b>(b)</b> False aneurysm in a 55-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image shows a false aneurysm of the left ventricular free wall (<b>*</b>), also a contraindication for transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig23b.jpeg" height="1334" width="1818" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. <b>(a)</b> True aneurysm in a 66-year-old woman who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image shows a left ventricular true aneurysm (<b>*</b>), a contraindication for transapical TAVR. <b>(b)</b> False aneurysm in a 55-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image shows a false aneurysm of the left ventricular free wall (<b>*</b>), also a contraindication for transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180059/asset/images/large/rg.2019180059.fig24.jpeg" height="1288" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Myocardial calcification in an 88-year-old man who underwent preprocedure evaluation for transapical TAVR. Axial multidetector CT image with intravenous contrast material shows myocardial calcification (arrow) of the left ventricular apex, a contraindication for transapical TAVR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180059&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Faggiano P, Antonini-Canterin F, Baldessin F, Lorusso R, D’Aloia A, Cas LD. Epidemiology and cardiovascular risk factors of aortic stenosis. <em>Cardiovasc Ultrasound</em> 2006;4(1):27.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/1476-7120-4-27">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16813661/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Epidemiology+and+cardiovascular+risk+factors+of+aortic+stenosis&amp;author=P+Faggiano&amp;author=F+Antonini-Canterin&amp;author=F+Baldessin&amp;author=R+Lorusso&amp;author=A+D%E2%80%99Aloia&amp;author=LD+Cas&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Cardiovasc+Ultrasound&amp;pages=27&amp;doi=10.1186%2F1476-7120-4-27&amp;pmid=16813661">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Osnabrugge RLJ, Mylotte D, Head SJ, et al. Aortic stenosis in the elderly: disease prevalence and number of candidates for transcatheter aortic valve replacement: a meta-analysis and modeling study. <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em> 2013;62(11):1002–1012.</div><div class="external-links"><div class